The world of September 11
NEW YORK – This week marks the 20th anniversary of the terrorist attacks on September 11, 2001, in the United States.
That day, 19 terrorists had taken control of four civilian aircraft, they crashed two of them into the towers of the World Trade Center in New York, hit the Pentagon with a third, and crashed a fourth plane in Pennsylvania after several passengers physically prevented the terrorists from reaching their target, which many believe was the White House or another U.S. government building in Washington, D.C.
All the hijackers were from the Middle East, and 15 of them from Saudi Arabia.
All had been trained in Afghanistan, and four in American flight schools, as part of an operation planned, organized, and carried out by Al-Qaeda (the "base"), a terrorist group led by Osama bin Laden.
At the end of the day, 2,977 men, women, and children innocent victims were mourned, and more than 6,000 were injured.
The majority were Americans, although citizens from over a hundred other countries also lost their lives.
Back then, many feared that September 11 had ushered in an era defined by global terrorism.
Indeed, other Al-Qaeda-led attacks followed, including several bombings in Madrid's trains in March 2004, then the attack in London's public transport in July 2005.
Terrorists aligned with the Islamic State (IS) also killed 32 people at Brussels' airport in March 2016, and instigated a series of smaller-scale attacks (often using vehicles to crash into pedestrians).
Pour autant, ni les États-Unis, ni aucun de leurs alliés n’ont jamais subi d’attentat d’une ampleur comparable à ceux du 11 septembre – qui sont sans commune mesure.
Il convient par conséquent de s’interroger : Au-delà des pertes immédiates, quelle différence le 11 septembre a-t-il produit ?
L’histoire a-t-elle changé et, si oui, dans quelle mesure ?
De nombreuses raisons expliquent pourquoi les terroristes ne sont pas parvenus à perpétrer d’autres attentats majeurs.
Après l’invasion américaine en Afghanistan, Al-Qaïda a perdu son sanctuaire.
Palmost all governments around the world have put in place procedures to make it more difficult for potential terrorists to access airports and airplanes.
States have significantly strengthened their intelligence, police, and military capabilities to minimize risks and counter threats.
They have also developed mutual cooperation, terrorism being one of the few areas where states, often in disagreement, are willing and eager to work together to a considerable extent.
There is now a broad consensus on what constitutes terrorism – the use of armed force by individuals and groups against civilians for political purposes – as well as a degree of support for the principle that governments should not differentiate between terrorists and those who provide sanctuary and support to them.
The time when individuals and groups ready to kill in the name of their cause were romanticized as freedom fighters is over.
<p>It is not about saying that terrorism has stopped claiming tens of thousands of lives every year.</p>
<p>However, nearly all attacks occur in the Middle East, Africa, and South Asia within the context of current conflicts (mainly in Iraq, Syria, Afghanistan, Libya, Somalia, Nigeria, Pakistan, and Yemen), as opposed to isolated attacks, like the 9/11 attacks, against major powers.</p>
<p>Terrorism is increasingly localized and decentralized.</p>
<p>It is also resilient: the capture or elimination of a terrorist organization leader does not necessarily mean the end of the group.</p>
<p>Al-Qaeda, for example, survived the elimination of Bin Laden by US special forces in Pakistan nearly ten years after the 9/11 attacks.</p>
<p>It is therefore not surprising that terrorism persists, with no resolution on the horizon.</p>
<p>The possibility of a new 9/11 cannot be ruled out either, despite the U.S. government recently stating that the "greatest terrorist threat" to the country exists domestically.</p>
<p>As the Provisional Irish Republican Army expressed after its failed assassination attempt on British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher in 1984: "We didn't have luck today, but remember we only need to have luck once. </p>
<p>You will always need it."</p>
<p>The danger lies in the fact that one day, terrorists will get their hands on nuclear material, or will manage to manufacture and use a biological or chemical weapon, in which case terrorism could define the era.</p>
<p>Pour l'heure, ce n'est pas le cas.</p>
<p>Le 11 septembre a pour autant marqué un tournant historique, avec un profond impact sur la politique étrangère américaine des 20 dernières années.</p>
<p>Si les attentats n'ont pas débouché sur une ère du terrorisme mondial, ils ont bel et bien engendré la fameuse guerre mondiale contre la terreur, avec des conséquences majeures dans le comportement des États-Unis à travers le monde, l'image de l'Amérique aux yeux du monde, et la manière dont de nombreux Américains ont fini par considérer la politique étrangère de leur pays.</p>
<p>La saga a débuté en Afghanistan.</p>
<p>Peu après les attentats du 11 septembre, les États-Unis ont proposé un choix aux talibans, qui contrôlaient alors le gouvernement afghan : livrer les responsables d'Al-Qaïda sur le point de quitter le pays, et coupables d'avoir organisé les attentats du 11 septembre, ou mettre en péril leur règne.</p>
<p>After the Taliban refused to hand over the leaders of Al-Qaeda, U.S. intelligence and military officials collaborated with an unstructured coalition of Afghan tribes called the Northern Alliance to overthrow the Taliban.</p>
<p>The United States contributed to the formation of a successor government that took control of most of the country.</p>
<p>This control, however, was never total or uncontested.</p>
<p>Many individuals loyal to the Taliban and Al-Qaeda sought refuge in the neighboring Pakistan, where they gradually rebuilt their strength and resumed military operations against the government that had replaced them.</p>
<p>Meanwhile, the United States did not sufficiently work to build an Afghan army, reduce corruption, and deprive the Taliban of sanctuary in Pakistan.</p>
<p>Au lieu de cela, the United States has reinforced its own presence and military operations in Afghanistan, essentially becoming a partner of the government in its civil war.</p>
<p>At its peak, U.S. intervention in Afghanistan mobilized over 100,000 American soldiers.</p>
<p>Over more than twenty years, the cost of operations reached over 2 trillion dollars, with over 2,300 American lives lost, and several tens of thousands among the Afghans.</p>
<p>The effort was both excessive and insufficient.</p>
<p>The American presence deprived the Afghan government of much of its legitimacy and sparked opposition to the United States, while the Taliban proved more persistent than America, which in 2020 had lost any desire to fight in a conflict destined to end in an indefinite stalemate.</p>
<p>Global war on terror also led the United States to go to war in Iraq.</p>
<p>It remains open whether President George W. Bush would have acted militarily without the 9/11 attacks.</p>
<p>The attacks certainly solidified his inclination to show the world that the United States was not, as President Richard Nixon had put it during the Vietnam War, a "giant impotent and pitiful."</p>
<p>This led some members of the administration (chief among them Vice President Dick Cheney) to refuse the risk of terrorists acquiring weapons of mass destruction, which Iraqi leader Saddam Hussein seemed to possess (it eventually turned out he did not) according to most protagonists.</p>
<p>Others aimed to spread democracy in Iraq, and throughout the entire Middle East, believing that such a move was not only feasible, but would also make the region much less likely to produce and support terrorists.</p>
<s>Déclenchée en mars 2003, la guerre en Irak ne s’est pas déroulée comme l’avaient souhaité ou prévu l’administration Bush ainsi que les nombreux membres du Congrès (dont Joe Biden, alors sénateur) et dirigeants mondiaux qui l’avaient approuvée.
<s>Les États-Unis n’étaient pas préparés à l’essentiel des événements à venir.
<s>Les victoires militaires remportées dans un premier ont certes permis de chasser le gouvernement, mais ont rapidement cédé la place à une agitation généralisée ainsi qu’à une guerre civile violente.
<s>La décision de dissoudre l’armée irakienne, et d’exclure des emplois gouvernementaux nombre d’Irakiens associés au régime précédent, a aggravé une situation déjà chaotique.
<s>Plus fondamentalement, l’Irak, à l’instar de l’Afghanistan, a démontré les limites de ce que peut accomplir la force militaire à un coût et dans des délais raisonnables.
<p>Ultimately, the United States was forced to reinforce its military presence, bringing it to nearly 170,000 soldiers, in order to preserve the besieged successor government in Baghdad.</p>
<p>A certain degree of stability was achieved, but at a considerable cost.</p>
<p>The United States spent at least as much in Iraq as in Afghanistan, but at a far higher human toll: over 4,000 American soldiers killed, a much larger number of wounded, and a dramatic increase in suicide rates among American military personnel (from Iraq as well as Afghanistan).</p>
<p>This total excludes deaths among private contractors and Iraqis, for which estimates vary widely, but which undoubtedly number in the hundreds of thousands.</p>
<p>The war in Iraq also weakened the United States in other ways.</p>
<p>Aucune preuve n’a jamais démontré l’implication de l’Irak dans les attentats du 11 septembre, et la réputation de l’Amérique a souffert lorsque l’argument d’une intervention militaire sans l’approbation de l’ONU – visant l’élimination des armes de destruction massive de Saddam – ne s’est révélée fondée sur aucune base réelle.</p>
<p>Les images de soldats américains maltraitant des prisonniers irakiens ont encore davantage terni la réputation du pays.</p>
<p>Par ailleurs, une Irak en guerre contre elle-même est devenue synonyme d’un Iran émergent comme le plus puissant pays de la région (ou l’un des deux plus puissants si l’on considère Israël).</p>
<p>Depuis la guerre, l’Iran a renforcé son influence sur l’Irak, la Syrie, le Yémen et le Liban.</p>
<p>L’Irak et l’Afghanistan se sont également révélés constituer deux distractions stratégiques majeures.</p>
<p>Pendant que les États-Unis s’impliquaient intensément au Moyen-Orient et en Asie du Sud, régions qui manquent de grandes puissances présentes et de dynamisme économique, l’équilibre géopolitique s’est déplacé en défaveur des États-Unis, à la fois en Europe et en Asie de l’Est, en raison de l’émergence d’une Russie plus agressive, ainsi que d’une Chine plus forte et plus affirmée.</p>
<p>La guerre mondiale contre le terrorisme ne pouvait pas fournir et n’a pas fourni aux États-Unis de boussole dans leur approche de politique étrangère à l’égard d’une rivalité renouvelée entre grandes puissances.</p>
<p>Les guerres menées à la suite du 11 septembre ont également entraîné d’importantes conséquences intérieures pour les États-Unis.</p>
<p>Elles ont ébranlé la confiance dans un pays qui était sorti de la guerre froide fort d’une puissance prépondérante historiquement sans précédent, et mis à mal l’unité nationale qui avait fait surface au lendemain immédiat des attentats.</p>
<p>Les coûts et les échecs associés à ces guerres ont par ailleurs alimenté l’opposition à un rôle mondial majeur et durable des États-Unis, donnant naissance à une nouvelle tendance isolationniste.</p>
<p>#1 <s>Similarly, this martial propensity, coupled with the global financial crisis of 2007-2009 and its economic repercussions, severely impacted American trust in elites, thereby fueling the rise of populist sentiment, which, among other consequences, contributed to the rise of Donald Trump.
<p>#2 <s>Today’s America is more divided than ever internally, and less inclined to pursue this form of active foreign policy that characterized it since the end of World War II, and which has largely benefited Americans as well as many others.
<p>#3 <s>With hindsight, we can now view 9/11 as a harbinger of what was to come: less globalization of terrorism than fears of globalization.
<p>#4 <s>The attacks conveyed the message that distance and borders mattered little in the age of globalization.
<p>#5 <s>Nothing remains local for long nowadays, whether it be terrorists born in the Middle East and trained in Afghanistan, or the effects of a global financial crisis whose origins lie in poor American financial management.
We are currently all facing a pandemic virus that has killed several million people since its appearance in China in December 2019.
Fires, droughts, floods, storms, and heatwaves that devastate many regions of the world are the consequence of climate change, itself the cumulative effect of human activity that releases enormous amounts of heat-trapping greenhouse gases into the atmosphere.
The era initiated by recent events comes full circle, marking the 20th anniversary of the American intervention in the country.
Twenty years ago, the Taliban were quickly chased from power; in recent weeks, they easily regained it.
It is too early to know if the Taliban will revert to their old habits by once again becoming a sanctuary for terrorism, and if terrorists from around the world will take pride in their victory over America and its allies.
<p>Ce que nous savons, en revanche, c’est que le terrorisme reste une caractéristique de notre monde.</p>
<p>Il ne définira pas l’avenir, mais demeurera l’un des aspects visibles d’une mondialisation qui pour sa part le détermine d’ores et déjà.</p>
